items.name: Michael C Hall
items.description:
Michael C. Hall is an actor most recognizable and known for playing Dexter Morgan on Showtime's TV series Dexter.

I saw another TI of Dexter, and thought it was decent, but I wanted to see if I could do any better since I was already planning to try my hand at him.

Trained on 25 images of Michael C. Hall as Dexter. Mostly screencaptures from the TV series.

I mostly used closeup for the dataset and trained his appearance, but not his attire or other elements from the show. I haven't messed around with LoRAs yet, but this seems like the type of thing that one of those would be useful for.

For what it's worth, I was going to showcase more images with Dexter stalking different people, but ran out of time so figured the couple I had were good enough. I have to learn Latent Couple or other techniques better to make better use of these types of photos.

items.name: Girls' Frontline-ZB26
items.description:
Role of Girls' Frontline

Weight 0.8~1.0 ,and you can ADJUST prompt to reductive character

TRIGGER:

1.BASE: gownZB26;

2.OG Gown: gloves, hat, black dress,white headwear, fur trim,

ᶘ ᵒᴥᵒᶅ
ᶘ ᵒᴥᵒᶅ
ᶘ ᵒᴥᵒᶅ

The ZB vz. 26 was a Czechoslovak light machine gun developed in the 1920s, which went on to enter service with several countries. It saw its major use during World War II, and spawned the related ZB vz. 27, vz. 30, and vz. 33. The ZB vz. 26 influenced many other light machine gun designs including the British Bren light machine gun and the Japanese Type 96 Light Machine Gun. The ZB-26 is famous for its reliability, simple components, quick-change barrel and ease of manufacturing. This light machine gun in the Czechoslovak army was marked as the LK vz. 26 ("LK" means lehký kulomet, light machine gun; "vz." stands for vzor, Model in Czech). ZB vz. 26 is incorrect marking because "ZB-26" is a factory designation (Československá zbrojovka v Brně), while "vzor 26" or "vz. 26" is an army designation.

In around 1921 the military of the young Czechoslovakian state embarked on a quest for a light machine gun of their own. Early trials included foreign designs and several domestic designs. Of these, the most important was the Praha II, a lightweight, belt-fed weapon built at Česka Zbrojovka (CZ) Praha (Czech Arms factory in Prague).

Development of the ZB-26 began in 1923 after the Czechoslovak Brno arms factory was built. Since CZ-Praha was a relatively small factory with limited industrial capabilities, it was decided to transfer the production of the new automatic weapon to the more advanced Zbrojovka Brno, or ZB in short. This transfer resulted in a long series of court trials over royalties, between the owners of the design (CZ-Praha) and the manufacturer (ZB). Designer Václav Holek was charged by the Czechoslovak army with producing a new light machine gun. He was assisted by his brother Emmanuel, as well as two Austrian and Polish engineers, respectively named Marek and Podrabsky. Holek quickly began work on the prototype of the Praha II and within a year the quartet had created an automatic light machine gun that was later known as the ZB.

Before long, the Holek brothers abandoned the belt feed in favor of a top-feeding box magazine and the resulting weapon, known as the Praha I-23, was selected. Despite the past legal troubles, manufacture of the new weapon had commenced at the ZB factory by late 1926, and it became the standard light machine gun of the Czechoslovak Army by 1928. The ZB-26 is a gas-operated, air-cooled, selective-fire machine gun. It has a finned, quick-detachable barrel and fires from an open bolt. Its action is powered by a long-stroke gas piston, located below the barrel. The gas block is mounted at the muzzle end of the barrel and also serves as the front sight base. The action is locked by tipping the rear of the bolt (breechblock) upwards, and into a locking recess in the receiver. The return spring is located in the butt of the weapon, and is connected to the bolt carrier/gas piston via a long rod; additionally, there is a short spring buffer located around the return spring at the juncture of the receiver and butt, which softens the impact of the bolt group at the end of its rearward stroke.

Its charging handle is located at the right side of receiver and does not reciprocate when the gun is fired. The ammunition feed is from a top-mounted box magazine made from sheet steel, holding just 20 rounds in a two-row configuration. The magazine housing has a forward-sliding dust cover. Spent cartridges are ejected downwards. The ejection port is normally closed with its own dust cover which opens automatically once the trigger is pressed. The trigger unit permits both single shots and automatic fire, selectable through a safety/fire mode selector lever situated at the left side of the pistol grip. The gun fires from an open bolt and the spring-loaded firing pin is operated by a projection on the bolt carrier, once the bolt is fully in battery and locked. Because of the overhead magazine, the sight line is offset to the left, and the front sight is mounted on a base which protrudes upward and to the left from the gas block.

The rear sight is attached to the left side of receiver, and has a range adjustment mechanism controlled by a knurled rotating knob. Standard furniture consists of an integral folding bipod, which is attached to the gas cylinder tube, and a wooden butt with a spring-buffered buttplate and a folding shoulder rest plate. Although the ZB-26 was intended for the light machine gun role, it was also offered with a sustained-fire tripod, and provided with a sufficient supply of full magazines and spare barrels it could serve (to some extent) as a medium machine gun. The same tripod was also adaptable for the anti-aircraft role.

items.name: Peaksel Wildcards: add variety to your boring subjects
items.description:
What is this?

A big set of tested values for different camera and color settings. Intended to give a big variety of results simply by adding a few words at the end of your prompt.

It gives you a huge number of possible image variations on top of your prompt. Works great both on characters and scenery.

How to use it?

You will need the wildcards extension. Extract the zip file to your wildcards folder (Path: stable-diffusion-webui-master\extensions\stable-diffusion-webui-wildcards\wildcards)

Positive prompt (full usage)

After "(your subject), (your style tags)", add:

(__peaksel_camerashotype__, __peaksel_camerashotangle__, __peaksel_camerabrand__, __peaksel_camerafilmsize__, __peaksel_camerafocus__, __peaksel_cameralensfocallength__), (__peaksel_colorscheme__, __peaksel_colortone__)

Random value from each of the lists will produce a result that may be this:

(gregnobodysd15 in a white shirt), (realistic, best quality, photo-realistic, best quality:1.3), (Medium shot, Eye Level Shot, shot by Leica camera, Shot on 8mm film, Split Diopter, 15mm lens), (Blush Pink, Champagne, and Sage Green colors, Soft colors)

Set your batch count to 20 and watch the show.

Bonus: Ultimate negative

Unfortunately, the wildcards extension is not working in the negative prompt, so feel free to copy-paste the content of "peaksel_negative.txt" directly.

Can be used on both characters and scenery, SFW and NSFW. You may need to add model-specific tags that fix the bugs if any, and (NSFW, nude, naked) if you are generating SFW characters.

This negative is on the mission to become the most complete one, so feel free to suggest important words if you see them missing. Not intended for anime models.

Your Negative prompt structure

(negative1, negative2), (peaksel_negative content), (model-specific tags: if needed), (SFW/NSFW tags: optional)

peaksel_negative.txt:

(out of the frame, out of the image, out of focus, canvas frame, cropped, duplicate), (watermark, signature, artist name, text, calligraphy, logo, censored, label, jpeg artifacts, username, software, UI, user interface, GUI, scribbles, error), (ugly, disgusting, blurry, poorly drawn, bad art, amateur, lowres), (worst quality, low quality, low rated, mediocre, bad composition:1.7), (deformed, distorted, disfigured:1.3), (bad anatomy, wrong anatomy, extra limb, missing limb, floating limbs), (mutated hands and fingers:1.4), (disconnected limbs, mutation, mutated, amputation:1.4), (conjoined fingers, deformed fingers, ugly eyes, imperfect eyes, skewed eyes, unnatural face, unnatural body), artist atelier

About the Library

All of these values are collected or generated by ChatGPt and then tested multiple times to make sure Stable Diffusion understands them and the results are distinctive enough from others. Boring results have been removed, so the lists are focused on quality rather than quantity.

Can add unexpected results to your mature prompt in text2image when hunting a good composition OR can be used for quick subject testing (like character embedding for example).

Have fun using it.

items.name: IronCatLoRA #4 - Fate/stay night: UBW Style
items.description:
IronCatLoRA #4 - Fate/stay night: UBW Style

Making LoRA's is a thing I do for fun. So if you like what I do? You can help me out by just using the LoRA and leaving a review!

So I like the Fate/ series a lot, I think it must be one of my most favorites' series/shows in anime (Light novels/VN's included). My first LoRA ever made was about one of my most favorites' character, Artoria Pendragon (Saber). So I was experimenting with making a style LoRA based of Fate/stay night: Unlimited Blade Works, since I also like the style of the show a lot. I think I've come to a point after multiple training sessions and testing with big image grids. That this LoRA does its job fairly well.

The style doesn't apply equally good to every checkpoint, but I think the style applies really well to YesMix. All off the current images I've uploaded are created with YesMix, with an exception of the example grids of course, they contain multiple checkpoints. I've offset the LoRA weight, so you can just use a weight of 1.0. This will in my vision give you the nicest possible style possible that will try to resemble the style of Fate/stay night: Unlimited Blade Works. No trigger word is needed, you just need to apply the LoRA.

In order to make it easy for you to see what the actual style changes, I've uploaded multiple image grids, that display multiple checkpoint and multiple concepts. This should hopefully give you an idea what the style on average will look like. It will of course depend on what checkpoint you use, so be sure to check the image grids out to get an idea. The columns that have no text above them, is the generation result from the checkpoint without this LoRA applied. I think for example the city, cityscape, sky styling carries really nice over from the show, also including night is really nice. All character images I've uploaded use the combination of those tags. I also think that trees and grass from the show carry over kinda nice. Feel free to experiment, I've trained this LoRA on all types of concept from the show, even food...

It's also possible to generate characters that occur in Fate/stay night: Unlimited Blade Works. The main characters are easier to generate though, the side characters are a bit harder to generate, but possible. Take a look at my character images I've uploaded to see how you can prompt them. You need to be specific in who the character is, sometimes increasing the weight of the character name might also help. The point of this LoRA is not to generate the characters, it's to apply the style of Fate/stay night: Unlimited Blade Works. I just noticed that's it's possible to generate the characters fairly well, so I've included examples. But you could combine my Artoria Pendragon LoRA with this LoRA in your prompting, to from what I've seen make really nice images, especially on YesMix. I've made an extra image post, with examples on how my Artoria LoRA looks with this style LoRA using YesMix.

items.name: 【Concept】Blank eyes/Hypnosis/催眠/Mind control
items.description:
A concept Lora aim to generate blank eyes girl and without too much interfering the style of the base model.

It appears that it can stably generate blank eyes without highres fix when generating portrait/close shot pictures.

But still, it is strongly recommended to enable highres fix, especially if you wanna generate full body images or images with detailed background, it can significantly improve the quality of blank eyes generation.

Works the best with anime styled base model, like NovelAI, Counterfeit, Anything series (which I used for testing), etc.

Lora trained on 272 images of blank eyes girls and used NovelAI as base model.

Recommand weight: 1. Trigger word: hypnoLora, empty eyes

Please feel free to leave a comment below :)

=============================================================================

概念类Lora，可以较稳定生成催眠，或者说“虚ろ目”、“blank eyes”类型的角色，而不会太多影响底模画风

在生成半身像、近景的时候效果最好，无需开启高清修复即可获得良好的blank eyes结果。

但依然强烈推荐开启高清修复，特别是在需要生成全身照/细节较丰富的背景的时候，可以极大提升眼睛生成的成功率。

最好使用NovelAI、Counterfeit、Anything之类偏动漫风的底模，半写实的底模效果也还行，但显然不如动漫风底模显著。

试了很多个版本，前前后后差不多一个多月。最终训练集有272张图片，底模是NovelAI的latest版本，用了85张blank eyes的脸部图片做正则化，取的15个epoch中的第12个作为最终版本，训练集重复次数为1

推荐权重：1左右 触发词：hypnoLora, empty eyes

有任何问题欢迎留言:)
